<br>
I decided to just go to the cafeteria rather than all the way up to my office, and I was greeted by what must have been half the building gathered there, standing around watching in horror on the televisions there. Then it was announced that the Pentagon had been hit and all hell broke loose, as those with friends or loved ones working there panicked and grabbed their cell phones, or ran back to their workstations to use the phone.<br>
<br>
I went back down to the courtyard for another cigarette, and everyone who smoked (we smokers recognize the regulars) was down there. Rumors were flying: a car bomb was found in the District somewhere, the Metro was shut down, there were more planes coming... It was impossible to get a cellular call through, regardless of what network you were on.<br>
<br>
By the time I had calmed down enough to go back upstairs, my Director was there, informing us that the VP of Operations had called, and all company personnel in NYC and DC were to go home immediately (our primary NYC location is about 6 blocks from the WTC site, and the building I was in was one of the taller buildings in Arlington). <br>
<br>
As people scrambled for rides, I got in the car for the short ride to Annandale. I didn't need to get on any freeways, so I don't know what it was like there, but on the streets under the bright sun, everyone was driving with their windows down and their radios blaring, usually WETA (the DC NPR station). Nobody was talking, nobody was honking, and the usually rude DC-area drivers were using turn-signals and being polite to one another. It was very, very surreal.<br>
<br>
Then we got home and began the frantic &quot;We're ok&quot; calls. Some of our relatives were relieved to hear from us. Some, like Mrs. Chase's mother, hadn't heard yet. It was during this that I found out from my little brother that my parents were in Massachussetts all week, and had been scheduled to fly home that day from Boston Logan. The airlines wouldn't tell us which flights had gone down, and the news still didn't know either. This was around 10:30 in the morning. It wasn't until 5:00-ish that I found out they were all right, and had been in line at the rental car counter when the airport shut down, so they were the first to get a one-way rental (this from a rental company that doesn't normally do one-way's). The drove a stewardess along with them to Toledo, Ohio, where she was picked up by her boyfriend who took her home to Detroit.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Chase and I just sat there, all day, glued to the television, watching in horror. Empathizing for all those families who wouldn't be getting any &quot;I'm ok&quot; calls. <br>
<br>
