<br>
The serenity I felt died the very next day and I’ve been unable to reclaim it since.  There I sat glued to the TV, shocked like most of the world – crying through all the disturbing images but unable to turn away.  That evening I tried to explain things to my children and I hated having to explain any of it because I felt like I was robbing them of some aspect of their childhood.  The monsters in storybooks don’t hold a candle to the ones in real-life.  <br>
<br>
But for the first time I felt that the Pledge of Allegiance had real meaning as I watched the American people pull together and truly become <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>indivisible</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  The local Wal-Mart ran out of flags – everybody was buying a flag, displaying flags – flags on cars, bikes, trees, homes, bridges – you name it! It seemed like everyone had a flag or a ribbon to show their support and commitment to their country. <br>
<br>
I don’t see too many flags anymore.  For me, I suppose 9/11 is a reminder that nothing lasts forever – peace doesn’t last nor does tragedy – not even a nation standing united will last forever.  I’ll never feel completely safe  – not like I did the day(s) before 9/11 - but I do take great comfort in knowing that if tragedy strikes again – I’ll be able to count on my neighbors, the people in my community and my country to help me get through it. <br>
<br>
